\section{Built-in tutorials}

The first release only supports built-in tutorials, so the registry can
be a plain tuple.  That keeps the embedding story simple: a host CLI can
add the tutorial subcommand without also inheriting package management
commands for installing external tutorials.

The example tutorial is intentionally small.  It teaches the student how
the per-step shell works, it produces a file in the dedicated workspace,
and it creates enough transcript material for the review command to show
something meaningful afterwards.

We also keep the prose short and paragraph-based.  The goal is not just
to validate shell commands, but to make the first-run experience readable
when it is rendered as Markdown in the terminal.

<<constants>>=
BUILTIN_TUTORIALS = (
    Tutorial(
        id="shell-basics",
        title="Shell Basics",
        summary=(
            "Inspect the workspace, create a file, and review what you did."
        ),
        steps=(
            TutorialStep(
                title="Inspect the workspace",
                instructions=(
                    "Run `pwd` and `ls`.\n\n"
                    "This shows where the tutorial stores its work for this "
                    "run."
                ),
                required_patterns=("pwd", "ls"),
                hint="The shell starts in the tutorial workspace.",
            ),
            TutorialStep(
                title="Create a note",
                instructions=(
                    "Create `notes.txt` containing the word `tutorial`.\n\n"
                    "One way is:\n\n"
                    "`printf 'tutorial\\n' > notes.txt`"
                ),
                check_command="test -f notes.txt && grep -q tutorial notes.txt",
                hint=(
                    "Any command sequence is fine if `notes.txt` exists "
                    "afterwards."
                ),
            ),
            TutorialStep(
                title="Review the note",
                instructions=(
                    "Display the file with `cat notes.txt`.\n\n"
                    "The transcript should show both the command and the "
                    "file contents."
                ),
                required_patterns=("cat notes.txt", "tutorial"),
                check_command="grep -q tutorial notes.txt",
            ),
        ),
    ),
)
@


\section{Listing tutorials}

The CLI needs an ordered list for display, so we expose the built-in
registry directly as an immutable tuple.

<<functions>>=
def get_tutorials() -> tuple[Tutorial, ...]:
    """Return the built-in tutorials in display order."""

    return BUILTIN_TUTORIALS
@

Let's verify that the example tutorial is visible to the CLI.

<<test functions>>=
def test_get_tutorials_returns_shell_basics():
    tutorials = get_tutorials()

    assert tutorials[0].id == "shell-basics"
